faqSchema:
  - question: "What is a Self-Directed Brokerage Account (SDBA)?"
    answer: "An SDBA is a feature within your employer retirement plan (401(k), 403(b), 457, 401(a), or federal TSP) that lets you invest in thousands of mutual funds and ETFs beyond the standard fund lineup. Think of it as a brokerage window inside your retirement plan — same tax treatment, same employer match, dramatically more investment options."
  - question: "Does my retirement plan offer an SDBA?"
    answer: "Many mid-to-large employers and the federal TSP do — but plans rarely advertise it. Common SDBA platforms include Fidelity BrokerageLink, Schwab Personal Choice Retirement Account (PCRA), Empower Brokerage, and Vanguard Brokerage Option. A Capital Wealth advisor can confirm your plan's eligibility on a complimentary 30-minute call."
  - question: "Who is eligible to use an SDBA?"
    answer: "If your employer plan offers an SDBA, every active participant is generally eligible regardless of income, job title, or investment experience. You don't have to be a senior executive or a high-net-worth investor to use it."
  - question: "Do I still control my 401(k) if I use an SDBA?"
    answer: "Yes. You keep full ownership and full control. When you engage Capital Wealth, we manage the investments inside the brokerage window on your behalf under a fiduciary agreement — but you still decide how much to contribute, when to change jobs, and whether to continue our engagement. You can adjust or end the advisory relationship at any time, subject to your plan's rules."
  - question: "Does my money leave my employer's 401(k) plan?"
    answer: "No. This is one of the most important things to understand about an SDBA — your money never leaves your 401(k). The brokerage window is an account inside your existing plan. You keep your employer match, your pre-tax or Roth tax treatment, and your ERISA creditor protections. There's no rollover, no distribution, and no taxable event."
  - question: "How is an SDBA different from a target-date fund?"
    answer: "Target-date funds assume every participant of a given age has the same savings, the same risk tolerance, the same outside assets, and the same tax picture — which simply isn't true. A professionally managed SDBA lets us build an allocation around your actual timeline, your other accounts (IRAs, taxable brokerage, your spouse's plan), and your risk comfort, and monitor it in real time."
  - question: "What does 'fiduciary' actually mean here?"
    answer: "Capital Wealth Advisors is a State of Utah Registered Investment Advisor. As a fiduciary, we are legally required to put your interests ahead of our own and to disclose any conflicts of interest. We don't earn commissions on fund selections — our only incentive is growing your retirement account responsibly over time."
  - question: "How often is my SDBA reviewed or rebalanced?"
    answer: "Continuously. We monitor portfolios in real time and rebalance when markets, your risk profile, or your plan circumstances change — not on a 'set it and forget it' schedule. We also coach semi-annually as life events (raises, kids, home purchases, job changes) reshape your plan."
  - question: "Will I still see my SDBA on my normal 401(k) statement?"
    answer: "Yes. Your brokerage window balance appears alongside your core account on a consolidated statement, and you can view both online through your plan provider (Fidelity, Schwab, Empower, Vanguard, TIAA, etc.). Specific features vary by platform."
  - question: "Is my money protected inside an SDBA?"
    answer: "Yes. Your funds stay inside your employer-sponsored 401(k), so they retain all of the plan's protections — including ERISA creditor protection in most cases. Nothing is withdrawn or moved outside your employer's retirement plan."
  - question: "Can I roll in prior-employer 401(k)s to my current plan?"
    answer: "In most cases, yes. Rollovers from previous employer plans into your current 401(k) are generally allowed and can simplify your picture dramatically. We'll walk through the tradeoffs on your call — sometimes consolidating in is best, sometimes leaving balances elsewhere (or moving them to an IRA) is the better choice."
  - question: "What happens to my SDBA if I leave my job?"
    answer: "You generally have four options: leave the balance in your former employer's plan, roll it into your new employer's 401(k), roll it into an IRA, or take a distribution (usually not advisable due to taxes and penalties). Each has different implications for fees, investment options, creditor protection, and ongoing advice. We'll help you weigh them when the time comes."
  - question: "Is an SDBA only for high earners or experienced investors?"
    answer: "No. Any employee whose plan offers an SDBA can participate — the feature is not limited to executives or high-income earners. That said, the benefit of professional management tends to scale with account size, so many participants explore this once their balance crosses the $100,000 mark."
  - question: "What are the 2026 401(k) contribution limits?"
    answer: "For the 2026 tax year, the IRS limit for employee contributions to a traditional or Roth 401(k) (or a combination of both) is $24,500. Age 50+ can add an $8,000 catch-up for a total of $32,500. Under SECURE 2.0, participants ages 60–63 may contribute an additional $11,250 'super catch-up' where the plan allows, for a combined total of $34,750. Employer match and profit-sharing are on top of these limits."
  - question: "How much does an SDBA cost?"
    answer: "Plan providers typically charge a small annual SDBA account fee (often $25-$50), plus fund expense ratios and any trading costs. Our advisory fee for managing the account is transparent, disclosed upfront, and billed directly against the SDBA — never as a hidden commission inside a fund."
  - question: "Can I stop using SDBA management later?"
    answer: "Yes. You can discontinue the advisory engagement at any time, subject to your plan's rules. Your money stays in your 401(k) throughout — nothing is taken out of your employer plan."
